04068nam a22005295i 9780231557870DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20242024nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315578707 a10.7312/fish209302doi  a(DE-B1597)679663  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aGE195 7aPOL0440002bisacsh04a363.7/06223/eng/202311301 aFisher, Dana R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSaving Ourselves :bFrom Climate Shocks to Climate Action /cDana R. Fisher. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2024] 4c©2024  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSociety and the Environment00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 No One Else is Going to Save Us: Understanding the Social Side of the Climate Crisis -- t2 Saving Ourselves is a Long Game: Why Our Institutions Keep Failing to Act on Climate -- t3 Saving Ourselves Involves Taking Power Back for the People -- t4 Saving Ourselves Won’t Be Popular and it Will Be Disruptive -- t5 Saving Ourselves Will Take a Disaster (or Many) -- tMethodological Appendix -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe've known for decades that climate change is an existential crisis. For just as long, we've seen the complete failure of our institutions to rise to the challenge. Governments have struggled to meet even modest goals. Fossil fuel interests maintain a stranglehold on political and economic power. Even though we have seen growing concern from everyday people, civil society has succeeded only in pressuring decision makers to adopt watered-down policies. All the while, the climate crisis worsens. Is there any hope of achieving the systemic change we need?Dana R. Fisher argues that there is a realistic path forward for climate action—but only through mass mobilization that responds to the growing severity and frequency of disastrous events. She assesses the current state of affairs and shows why public policy and private-sector efforts have been ineffective. Spurred by this lack of progress, climate activism has become increasingly confrontational. Fisher examines the radical flank of the climate movement: its emergence and growth, its use of direct action, and how it might evolve as the climate crisis worsens. She considers when and how activism is most successful, identifying the importance of creating community, capitalizing on shocking moments, and cultivating resilience. Clear-eyed yet optimistic, Saving Ourselves offers timely insights on how social movements can take power back from deeply entrenched interests and open windows of opportunity for transformative climate action.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCOVID-19 Pandemic, 2020-xInfluence. 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspects. 0aEnvironmentalism. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Environmental Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074968740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/fish2093040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231557870423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231557870/original  a978-3-11-074968-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles